Austria's right-wing populists win 29%
The appreciable weakening of both sides of the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of right-wing populist parties brought early parliamentary elections in Austria, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (<0xC3><0x96>VP) suffered particularly heavy losses, where the position of the current chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously shaken.
In contrast, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZ<0xC3><0x96>), Carinthian Governor J<0xC3><0xB6>rg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, it remains the strongest party in the country of social democracy (SP<0xC3><0x96>) with 29.8% of the vote, but it loses 5.5% of the vote against the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the <0xC3><0x96>VP, which lost by 25.6% to almost 9% of the vote.
These are the worst results of both of these major parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, a literally disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the <0xC3><0x96>VP withdrew from the coalition, the People’s Party had a significant advantage over the SP<0xC3><0x96>.
But voters have clearly punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of the party’s chairman and former Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the still most likely outcome of the election, i.e. the renewal of the grand coalition of SP<0xC3><0x96> and <0xC3><0x96>VP.
However, due to the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FP<0xC3><0x96>) received a preliminary 18 percent and the BZ<0xC3><0x96> 11 percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed concern about the repetition of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at that time the FP<0xC3><0x96> was still united, in 2005 even broke away from the BZ<0xC3><0x96> party) on a common government.
This development is clearly supported by Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with any party and envisages a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Green Party also got into the parliament, but it was slightly lost and fell among the Austrian political parties from third to fifth place.
None of the other parties apparently crossed the 4% threshold and did not get into parliament.
