Travel Agents Record Increasing Numbers of Reservations
It seems that winter will be good for German entrepreneurs in tourism:
According to one study, travel bookings for the coming months increased significantly in turnover compared to the previous year – by even more than 30 percent for the winter season.
Despite weak economic growth, the desire of Germans to travel remains undiminished.
For bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded a 31 percent increase in turnover compared to the same period last year, as the German Travel Association (Deutscher Reiseverband, DRV) said on Monday in Berlin.
According to a survey by the market research institute GfK, increased bookings are already available for the autumn months.
According to DRV, the turnover in October was about eleven percent higher compared to 2007.
These results are based on GfK figures, which evaluates booking data from 1,200 German travel agencies every month and interpolates it into the overall market.
This result included bookings of tours that took place until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar exchange rate, travel to the United States is especially in demand, DRV said.
For these trips, the increase in bookings makes about one-third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as domestic waters, are particularly desirable targets for the Germans.
Especially organized tours are in the course, said DRV Chairman Klaus Laeple.
In view of the rising costs of energy and food, the costs here are "more calculable for the client than for an individually organised holiday".
Laeple explained that money can be saved by consumers, among other things, by using early booking discounts or all-inclusive offers.
Even in the summer months, the number of bookings was said to be very good, so there will again be a higher turnover compared to the previous year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who took some sort of trip fell compared to the previous year.
