Turkey's diplomatic horizons widened
Long before Turkey began its bid to join the European Union, the European powers wanted to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the east bank of the Bosphorus, perhaps just twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the finest monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
A tourist guide will tell you that.
The building sits in a circle at the end of the platform with a tower on each corner of the facade, looking indistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the vaulted cash register, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gate was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium of the Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to realize its ambitions for the control of the Middle East with the help of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and further on in the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their dormitories were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
British and colonial troops marched out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a Station as well.
In 1917, an explosion of an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, they have gradually crumbled and history has bypassed them.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is being implemented - Turkey is engaging.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a curvy ride on the tracks that recalled the old-world rhythms of the famous Night Post, I arrived in the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi brought me to the AKP's main tent, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, purposely built on a sprawling suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power shops, where middle managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning deals.
Suat Kiniklioglu could well be a middle-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
“The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey was cut off from its own land.
We have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
He had to do both.
"But there will come a time," I asked, "when Turkey may have to make a decision?"
"Turkey," he said, "didn't want such a decision to have to happen."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to said almost by heart: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, follow these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a Station, after another long night, I thought of the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Con, who had watched the building being built a hundred years ago.
How would they be surprised to learn that European ambitions in the Middle East could now be, in large part, in Turkish hands?
And when I was waiting at the port for the ferry back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford Music Director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
As part of the district music plan, he founded a year-long excellent choir of young Proteus.
He was supposed to be 21 years old, but by the time Proteus sang for the last time in 1979, a few of us were almost 30 — we just refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (mythological shape-shifter) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to engage in any music presented to it - whether madrigals or Messiaen, either alone or with the whole orchestra.
The musical adaptability created by such a young choir was often overwhelming, always exciting, and all thanks to the inspiration of that one man and the enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely unchanged all the time.
How often has Tod told us to "let the music speak for itself"?
He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the music.
Sing it then! "
His tactics were clear and precise, but they were neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever there was a standard of music, it always raised it.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor was to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well for two decades, when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
I’ve reviewed over 100 of his concerts over the last 40 years, and I can honestly say that I’ve never been disappointed by any of them – and I’ve been inspired many times.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of size and personal modesty.
He hated conductors, who, in his words, simply "dragged one or two seeps around the world."
Many of us will be missed.
