"Car Bee" Prevents Collisions
To advance the development of technologies to protect against accidents, Nissan this time inspired in nature, specifically in bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the pattern of flying bees, thus preventing collisions.
Such is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Centre for Technological Progress have developed the robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advances in Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology, Research and Brand Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four safety shield zones.
The robot is designed to strengthen the ability to prevent collisions in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the most important are the compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
When creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are up to two meters within a 180-degree radius of the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even a larger angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down or diagonally; its movement is limited to only two dimensions and the direction in which it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities, as in bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent collisions.
“The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and to be preserved according to this data.
It does not require the storage of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, thanks to which it can work without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but in memory we don’t talk about gigs or megas.”
This is the first step in the development of new crash prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination and avoid obstacles on the way.
