Morgan Stanley has announced that Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan’s largest bank, is entering its midst, spending $9 billion to raise 21% of its capital. The adoption of this report was accompanied by a significant drop in its exchange rate.
A week after they revealed their preliminary agreement, both banks explained that MUFG plans to buy 9.9 percent of Morgan Stanley’s common stock at a single price of $25.25, a total of $3 billion.
The agreed price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as of August 31.
MUFG is investing an additional $6 billion in convertible securities, which will provide it with a 10% return and an exchange price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the entire operation would take place on the basis of an average unit price of $29, or 28% below its current exchange rate.
Morgan Stanley's shares were still down 6.79% to $23.07 at around 5 p.m.
“This strategic merger represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to a banking holding company,” said John Mack, Group CEO.
The new statute was adopted by Morgan Stanley last week to allow it to diversify its activities, but it also places it under the supervision of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Its merger with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest ace to take a far more cautious approach than before.
The terms unveiled on Monday show, among other things, that the deal has been amended over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan only announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for around $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, we thought," Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG's chief executive, explained in Tokyo, "that our participation would consist exclusively of ordinary shares.
However, given the current state of the economy and the market, we wanted to keep the risks to a minimum and also to cover ourselves."
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay for Morgan Stanley securities 7 % less than their book value.
And the operation will result in a reduction in earnings per share of about 20%.
The agreement envisages that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares within a year, if the latter are exchanged for a certain period at a price exceeding the exchange price by 50%, i.e. for about $ 47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital that MUFG will bring will allow it to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its cash.
However, the group's spokesperson declined to provide further details on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
Following the investment by MUFG, Morgan Stanley should boast a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15 %, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had "tangibly" cut his balance since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, as its exchange rate has fallen by half, while the insurance costs against the risk of non-payment associated with debt have risen sharply.
On Monday, these costs took the opposite turn, but remained high, at around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of Wall Street’s big investment banks after the Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers crash and the Merrill Lynch buyout, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Warren Buffett’s Berkshire Hathaway.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
To re-establish a republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
Such is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
Last Sunday, the third nominee put to the vote, following the example of his counterparts and friends, a draft of a new Constitution.
And his mission is fulfilled, because 64% of voters, according to official results covering 80% of the vote, voted "yes" in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% of the votes received "no", 7% were invalid and 0.7% of the ballots were empty.
In order to pass the bill, he had to get half the votes plus one.
Two polls conducted in the east of the polling stations and a calculation by NGOs predicted a clear "yes" victory on Sunday, placing them in the range of 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa, on the other hand, demanded the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has won," he assured and congratulated the Ecuadorians at Guayaquil, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
It goes without saying that Rafael Correa received congratulations from Chavez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which, according to the Organization of American States (OEA) observation mission, took place quietly, concerned the text on 444 points building the "new socialism" promoted by the president.
The draft Constitution sanctifies the power of the state over the economy by depriving it of "development planning" of a country living primarily on oil extraction by foreign companies and on foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
The proposal, backed by Correa, who was elected in 2006, also expands the powers of the head of state, who will be able to serve two consecutive four-year terms and be able to dissolve the chamber.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The constitution, among other things, reinforces the principle of free health care and education that the president has begun to implement in a country of 13.9 million people, where 50 percent of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also envisages a ban on the presence of foreign troops, thus ending the agreement between Washington and Quito on the use of the Ecuadorian base as the starting point of US drug operations.
19 hostages have been freed in Chad.
An Egyptian commando carried out an attack on the hijackers of 11 tourists and their eight-member escort, who were captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for 10 days, were transported alive and well to the Egyptian capital on Monday.
In the morning, an Egyptian commando liberated them in Chad.
The hostages arrived around 3:30 p.m., apparently in good form, aboard a special aircraft to al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported, without being able to speak in the press, on board a helicopter to a hospital in Maadi, a suburb of Cairo’s residential district, to undergo medical examinations.
“They are perfectly healthy” and “no ransom has been paid to the hijackers,” Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheyr Garrana said on the airport’s runway.
Since their capture on September 19, during a four-wheel-drive safari at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages has been dragged from one hideout to another by 35 unknown hijackers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard director of the Aegyptous agency, the organisers of the safari.
A senior Egyptian security official has suggested that 30 special forces members who approached the site on board two helicopters went on a rampage during the night just before dawn.
"There was a shootout, half the kidnappers were killed and the others fled," said the source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He indicated that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces from the “flash” unit were sent to Sudan, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy, Franco Frattini, from Belgrade, where he is now, mentioned the role played by secret agents and Italian special forces.
“We have to recognize that we achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of people from our intelligence services, special forces,” he said.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve of the raid, the Sudanese army said it had detained a four-wheel-drive vehicle carrying hijackers, killing six including the Chadian commander and arresting two others.
The army claimed they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement - Unity (SLA-U), which immediately rejected the movement.
