Government of Benelux State Bank Fortis
The Benelux countries will help Fortis, the Belgian-Dutch bank that was the first in Europe to get into trouble due to the growing impact of the US mortgage market crisis, with a partial nationalisation: the three countries will support a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion money and insurance institution, which also has a capital stake in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed at the highest level, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Fortis is the first bank in the euro area to be hit by a major crisis in the context of a crisis of international financial markets, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions taken on this matter could be seen as precedents from a certain point of view.
According to the decision, which was born on Sunday night, all three states will buy almost half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets there.
The bank is confident that it will sell some of its equity holdings, most notably - mainly insurance - activities purchased last year from Dutch bank ABN Amro.
The shares of Fortis Bank began to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week there were already serious signs of a crisis in the institution.
But analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to fail.
The company's securities fell 12 percent on Friday alone, to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current share prices, the total market capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s leaders, this is unrealistic.
The company blames the fall of Fortis shares on the uncertainty in the overseas market associated with the adoption of the plan of the US package worth $ 700 billion.
On Monday, the shares rose slightly.
On Friday, a new CEO, Filip Dierckx, was appointed to head the bank.
The Money Institute was also looking for private buyers, but no one has yet come forward with a more serious offer.
The Belgian government has already announced that investors do not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
There has been no panic among the bank’s clients and the branches have not been taken by the attack.
Fortis has a separate branch in Hungary and has also acquired several leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people's data on the purchase of medicines, often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with the applicant.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to the fox,” Richard Dick, the author of a program designed to monitor drug prescriptions, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make insurance premiums and amounts paid in the case of insurance events dependent on the health status of the interested parties, and if the risk is assessed as too large, they will not even conclude insurance with it.
They used to send the people in question for medical examinations and only concluded the contract when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, a customer from pharmacies can easily find out what drugs he bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself deduces what kind of disease he suffers from and what his state of health is.
For example, if he regularly buys a large amount of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this indicates that he has virtually uncontrollable high blood fat levels, which immediately puts him in a category with a higher risk.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which determine the risk ratio at the same time, so the insurance company has almost no work left besides paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include the fact that several drugs can be used for several purposes, some compounds, for example, are useful against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-increasing factor, whereas the aforementioned difficulties do not.
In order to request and process data, special companies have been created, which, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, will ask the patient for permission.
The authorities are now forcing them to do so, even though they have not been punished for their negligence.
Recently, some companies have been processing the results of laboratory tests, which they combine with data on the drugs used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, while controlling their use will become increasingly difficult.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give authorities the power to control even companies specializing in providing data, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his programme in such a way that the transfer of data is subject to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that the permission in question can hardly refuse, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with it.
So the hens are still somewhat reliant on the leaf of good will.
The global Marseille menu
EU and India to double trade turnover
As the European Union and India are each other’s leading trading partners, this topic dominated the agenda of the Ninth Summit, along with other, mostly global, issues.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, which will focus on cooperation in the field of nuclear energy.
The European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic power that should be given a greater say in international affairs, but the member states have so far failed to find a common denominator in support of New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This issue was thus not discussed further at yesterday's, already the ninth summit, held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, respectively President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso and High Representative for Foreign Affairs Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they also agreed that trade turnover will double within five years, or rise to more than one hundred billion euros.
With trade in goods rising from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
In a sign of this, twenty-six existing bilateral agreements on civil aviation with India were legally aligned, so that air transport was also given the green light in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised that negotiations would be accelerated.
The aim is to balance the balance, while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi ranks ninth among the EU’s partners.
The summit also focused on global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, respectively terrorism, has been condemned by both sides in all its forms and called for the speedy convening of a UN conference.
They also called for the conclusion of the Doha Round of trade negotiations, although both have a large share in its failure to date.
The European Union has confirmed that it will insist on its energy and climate agenda, namely that it wants to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed, as well as the need to conclude a global agreement at next year’s climate conference and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
Both sides would also like to prevent food price hikes and support the convening of an international conference to analyse the financial crisis.
The Indian prime minister will travel to the French capital today, where he plans to close a deal on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
Paris believes that the mandate for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors worth 20 billion euros will be given to French companies.
According to agency reports, the agreement would be valid for 15 years.
