Large participation of Italian publishers at the international book fair in Frankfurt.
More than three hundred Italian publishers will attend the 60th edition of Buchmesse, the most important international meeting for the exchange of rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair expects more than seven thousand exhibitors from one hundred and one different countries to take up 171,790 square meters of the fair, with more than four hundred and three thousand titles to see, with Turkey as the guest of honor.
Deputy Culture Minister Francesco Maria Giro will represent the Italian government at the inaugural ceremony in the Italian Pavilion: Italy will in fact participate institutionally with the Italian Centre (Punto Italia) – on 264 square metres of exhibition space.
This will be followed by a press meeting in Room Structures Buchmesse in Hall 5.0: it will be an opportunity to present the numbers, trends and perspectives regarding the state of publishing in Italy.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign authors in relation to the total Italian production is constantly decreasing, mainly due to the literature for children and adults.
The plane of Steve Fossett, a millionaire who disappeared a year ago
The rest of Steve Fossett's plane, a millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was discovered on a plateau at an altitude of three thousand meters, in the Mammoth Lakes area of Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
There were no human remains inside the plane.
The Madeira County Sheriff, John Anderson, dispelled the doubts that still remained: “The plane was found, we sent a team there and now we are sure that this is exactly where Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared,” he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old millionaire has been presumed dead since February.
The U.S. Transportation Security Bureau (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the debris was identified, an investigation team was dispatched to finally identify the plane: it was exactly Bellanc 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal items were found by one couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents with Fossett’s name on them, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, for cash and one jacket.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
